values: Last night when Emilio and I walked out of White Spot into the parking lot after dinner, the air was laced with the sweet scent of spring. I am giddy with anticipation.

2. Boo
3. ia

3. Autism support worker

Thinking of Europe.

Edit:

dropped two of my courses, going to europe in May, work permitting.

I am lacking in commitment right now. I am a sack of homework and writing, and yet when I get inspired by the art of the path I left behind I'm so quick to throw it all to the way side and muse and obsess over the beauty that I used to be able to create, long to create it again. Maybe I need to include that in my life, but maybe I need to commit somehow. Otherwise the ideas are half assed and get no where. Maybe I need to turn away from performance-based works, but find something that still exploratory and progressive.

I'm thinking site specific photography/short film: Bodies and Landscapes.

This Summer will be intense! I am going to be doing a full course load, one distance, one intersession, one summer session, and one regular.
  • EDUC 315 - Individual Differences in Language Acquisition
  • PSYC 388 - Biological Rhythms and Sleep
  • PSYC 354 - Development of Children's Thinking
  • CRIM 104 - Something about criminal behaviour (it's a breadth credit)
And I have two classes with the lovely miss sophie, hopefully we'll be able to pool our studying efforts and get maximal grades with minimal work.

I'll also be taking one of the children I work with to some preschool programs for a month, which should be cool. I also dropped two of my commitments, and am taking on another family for different experience/more pay. It's a no lose (except for the families that I left) situation.

I'm at odds at what to do about the rest of my degree: Douglas college is offering a citation in ABA/Disability which can be transferred to SFU and count towards my degree. In the fall it starts and goes year-round for 3 semesters. I could do that concurrently with my remaining SFU coursework and have one semester left in fall 2011 to finish up my degree. The only downside to that, is that I will be very busy and won't have a ton of time to work, which means that I won't be able to acrue many certification hours and will have to wait longer between finishing my coursework and writing the board exam to be a BCABA (associate behavour analyst). If I delay the douglas coursework, I could probably finish off all of my SFU courses by Fall 2011 and then start the coursework while working a little more intensively. So basically I have to decide if I want to have no life and be done sooner but get less supervision, or if I want to take a little longer but work more. Honestly I think the first one is better, because once I graduate even if I'm still gaining the supervision hours I can work as a b-level consultant anyways. Besides, maybe I wont even want the certification then after all.

ok. end rant, back to studies.

SO GLAD the LJ banner is leaves and not easter eggs. Although, I'm not sure why. Upcoming earth hour/day? Seems a little far away.....

I will be 21 in three days, excitiiinnggg!!! Although I think I've been cheating because in all the research participation I've had to do for my psyc class I've been writing 21 instead of 20 on the questionnaires. Just feels more accurate! Come on year 21, I am ready for yooouz!

p.s. just tried to post this and I'm using my mom's hella old laptop she had laying around in her office. Autodate LJ chose for me is December 31st, 1969 at 4:16 pm. What? How does that even happen?

So all of these days I have been freezing in my mother's office and could not find the switch to turn on the heating apparatus. I have also been chilling with the light off, since there is this huge window in here that makes artificial light redundant. At any rate, today I decided to see if turning on the light would activate the heat and, lo and behold! Warmth. 

I even tried draping a little blankie over me while shivering through my essay writing on early Gestalt psychology, but the thing was so dusty it made me sneeze.

I don't even try writing about life anymore. I feel like since I can't do it justice, writing about it just makes it seem bleak. 

I went to my second contact improv class. I was very nervous and timid at first. It's hard for me to be in such an unfamiliar environment, when I am much more inexperienced in the skill being practiced than everyone else. Especially since it involves interacting with others by means of that skill set. But if felt so good to listen to my body and move how my body wanted to move, and slow dooown. I was hesitant to move into contact with the others, and the first few attempts were feeble and awkward. But later on I saw an interesting opportunity. A man was moving towards me, along the edge of the marley and making a play on the linear line with his body. I actively did the opposite; swirling, swooping and low motions. And when we met, while still awkward at times and in need of negotiation, it flowed beautifully in moments. Instead of trying to get "on", we were actually dancing together, rarely breaking contact. we started slow, my hands in his, making shapes, moving into and out of the floor. There were pauses when we were stuck, but by listening we could flow through. We picked up speed, arms making more intricate shapes, legs moving more quickly, taking up space in the room. I began to grow tired, and eventually broke away to go sit with the experience. It was intimate, and yet with a total stranger. I have never spoken a word to him, except for one "sorry" and one "it's okay". I don't even know his name. And yet what we created was so painfully beautiful, the memory of it is still dancing in my head. 

This is what I've been searching for; dancing for dancing's sake, and dancing in a way that calls for surrender.

ugh.

day time drunk is fun but only up until you start breaking shit.

We got out of bed at 2pm and went to Ihop for b-fast. Yummiiiieeess althought I was super sad that my crepes didn't come with Bacon, but meels shared. I needed nailpolish remover so we hit up the london drugs then went down to the skate park with builder, les and joel. Pretty uneventful but it was fun to skate again. Apparently I can still kind of ollie. wuuutt! 
Then they went for dinner, but we had just had breakfast, so we went grocery shopping and met up at their place later on for some beer and foosball. 
Came home at 9:30 ish to find alexx had made dinner! Watched skins, drank some wine, went to sleep.

Pretty good as far as v-days go. Although we did have an intense what is the meaning of love? convo in the morning and talked about OUR FUTURES! ffft. 

Saturday night we went to see the national ballet and royal winnipeg ballet as an early b-day present from my rents. Pretty crazy there, we couldn't find anywhere to have a beer after that didn't have coveerrr. Tons of people, and they have some crazy pavilion type thingies set up (like the aboriginal pavillion and the irish pavilion) which have huuge lineups and supposedly 25$ cover bleck. 

And I think I should mention that saying bye to bradem was super sad :( I'm going to miss that crazy guy! But we have turned his room into an office, which I am currently sitting in, and now we have a closet for our vacuum and for guests to put their coats in.

<![endif]-->  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 6pt; text-indent: 36pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";">I am pleased to offer my application to the Capilano University ABA-A degree program. Working in the field of Applied Behaviour Analysis has ignited in me a passion to learn, grow and help others.<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 6pt; text-indent: 36pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";">In April of 2008, I was introduced to a family seeking a Behavioural Interventionist for their six year old non-verbal daughter, diagnosed with autism and partial epilepsy. Unsure of what to expect, I was drawn to the challenge of creatively relating to an individual while simultaneously building the motivation and interest necessary for a child to learn.<span style="">  </span>Since then I have broadened my knowledge and skills of ABA through workshops and additional experience. In May of 2009 I was promoted to the lead therapist position managing four other therapists, and have since successfully balanced work and school responsibilities; my commitment to the children I work with has not hindered my full-time education. It is the deeply rewarding achievement of helping individuals in need which makes ABA my career of choice.<span style="">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 6pt; text-indent: 36pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";">I believe whole-heartedly in the principles of ABA. I am able to see firsthand what a profound effect quality treatment has on the lives of children with autism and their families. During my work I have faced numerous challenging situations and behaviours: head-directed self injury, self restraint, tantrumming and aggression are a few examples. These experiences have not thwarted my love of the field; I take every day that I work as an opportunity to learn, grow and teach. <o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 6pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";"><span style="">            </span>The ABA-A program offers the rare specialisation that I feel I am ready for. Upon completing the program, I intend to obtain my BCaBA certification, acquire the necessary experience to be included on the RASP, and begin consulting under the supervision of a BCBA. Eventually, I would attend graduate school either for ABA or Dance-Movement therapy. I believe the passion I have for helping others will allow me to effect significant positive change in the lives of many. <o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-indent: 36pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";">Thank-you very much for your consideration of my application to this program; I look forward to hearing from you. <o:p></o:p></span><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";"><o:p><br /></o:p></span></p>    <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";">Sincerely,<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";"><o:p> </o:p></span><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";"><o:p><br /></o:p></span></p>    <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";">Maria Turner<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-family: "Book Antiqua","serif";">Lead Behavioural Interventionist<o:p></o:p></span></p></meta></meta></meta></meta>

The (well, an) electrician came today, so hopefully I will no longer need to shower in fear. I've actually been refusing to shower alone, and making Emilio touch the knobs (suggesting he uses latex gloves, of course). I am a paranoid android. ooooooh wells, at least I knows it.

Last night we went for all you can eat fish'n'chips at the cockney kings (and forgot to invite john b.). Soph and Jase came with, then we went back to our place and played cranium. We had to make play doh since the shit we had was all rotten.

Turns out Bradem is leaving next Saturday. It will be sad to see him go, but we are most deffinitly looking forward to actually having somewhere to sit and work in our house. "On the bed" isn't really cutting it for me.

hopefully tripple-o's is still serving b-fast. All I've had today is a banana and a cup of tea. I'm going to get some sustenance, then some coffee, and then study. We will see how that goes.

I randomly quit journaling, so I guess it's nice to throw something in here every once in a while.

Last week was nuts. I had a midterm, an assignment, two rehearsals and a show. And I was sick. But I managed. I think I am officially no longer a dancer. It was kind of our last shot at performing with SFU, anyways, so now anything I want to do will be with the professional community and take some actual effort. We re-did "its rather dark in here" and Bradem mixed the music. Didn't get picked for the mainstage though. Boo. At least my mother darling got to see it when she was in town.

Afterwards we went to Santi and Deborah's. Their house is beautiful! Their little rug-rat was asleep, but they have another one on the way! They did a total re-mod on this run down place near Nanaimo and 6th. It's exactly where I hope I can live in the future. Emilio and I are talking about how poor we are, where we'd like to be etc if we don't hate each other in another 2 months. We were discussing putting ourselves on a wait-list for some buildings in the Main st. area, and then maybe in two years... bah. It's all speculation anyways. 

I sent off my application yesterday... fingers crossed.

So I got a good electrical shock in the shower this morning, apparently there's a current running through our pipes. 

On the plus side, since I jumped out of the shower in fear, I didn't get a chance to rinse to shampoo out of my hair. So I rinsed in the kitchen sink sans conditioner and I kind of like the effect. Maybe I will quit conditioner.
Coming home at 1am, drunk, thinking your car's been stolen because its not sitting in front of your house, when your boyfriend just took it to mcdonalds without asking.

Resolutions:

# 1: Eat breakfast tomorrow is DONE! Although it was breakfast food, it was 2pm, so not sure if that counts.
# 2: Ballet 2x/week

I think that's it.

One more day of fall semester, and I still can't manage to actually study. Tomorrow Soph and I both finish our exams at 10:30, then its off to the pub! Beer!!

I had two exams yesterday. it was bruuuutal. I wrote my math exam in a tiny little room with one window and I kept getting eraser crumbs everywhere and then I had to blow them off the table, but then I had to erase more stuff. It was quite annoying. I hope my prof got the exam, I left it with the woman across the hall. 

My padre is officially retired, and the district put on a little presentation. It was nice to see some of my sibblings for once. We went to Milestone's after, apparently just missing phoenix. Them Emilio and I had to make it up to the uni to babysit the two little guys. 

I need to stuudddyyy for my last exxaaaaammmmm.......

oh! B- in physics. Talk about awesome!

Upcoming Show:

Friday, December 4th 2009 at the SFU Theatre. Time, TBA. 

I will be performing in a ~4min duet that Sophie and I choreographed, (loosely) based on the poems and drawing of Shel Silverstein. Its kind of dark and quirky, but so are the poems. Come if you can!

This was a last minute affair, we decided we were going to do a piece on Tuesday, had our first rehearsal yesterday, and just made it for the sign-up. On the plus side, after being depressed for the past month and losing my motivation entirely last week to the point where I didn't even try and do my math assignment (and it wasn't hard) I'm noticing that maybe this whole "science" thing really isn't for me. I think the balance I'm looking for means keeping dance, physicality and creative expression in my life.

I took my first "meditation" walk between classes today. I was noticing that when I walk slowly, I pretty much lose my balance very slightly with every step. I was determined to do the equivalent of a lap around the AQ very slowly. I got a lot of strange looks, but the funny part was when I ran into Jason and he was all "wow, you're walking really slow" and then I had to explain to him what I was doing and of course sounded a little off the deep end, so to speak. I'm ok with that. 

It feels good to be a dancer again.

A Tree House
 
A tree house, a free house,
A secret you and me house,
A high up in the leafy branches
Cozy as can be house.
 
A street house, a neat house,
Be sure and wipe your feet house
Is not my kind of house at all~
Let's go live in a tree house.

Shel Silverstein

So I actually did half dec on my math/phys midterms. Above average in both! 71% in physics and 74% in math. I'm happy with that, considering I landed a whopping 48% of math midterm one, which believe it or not was one above average. 

School poo! I'm planning my life for the next three years, at which point I should finally be able to say I have a degree. I'm taking nothing but 3 psyc courses next semester. I am so happy about it! I will have time! And a life! 

On the downside I think I've come down with some chronic fatigue and mild depression. Called up my daddy on thursday balling, talk about embarrassing. 3 breaks downs in one week, someone should get me in the bath more often. And tell me to chill the fuck out. Emilio has been fantastic, unfortunately now he's got a cold and I will have to make my own damn licorice tea.

Oh, and I finally got up off my fat ex dancer's ass and did some yoga yesterday, and of course I strained my shoulder. Then when I got home I was so tired I had to curl up into a ball for an hour. Getting back into shape is going to be a little harder than I originally imagined.

Ok this is officially considered rambling, I have nothing of importance to say.

Babysitting is fun, usually, until the days when you're at science world and one kid starts crying that he wants to leave and then the other starts crying that he doesn't and you're half way between the theatre entrance and the concession stand and all the moms are looking at you like you don't know how to handle these kinds and while you turn around to pick the little guy up the other one tries to run away.

I had a bath today and went out with soph for some tea. The starbucks guy was blatantly and shamelessly hitting on me, and it was strange because a. I never get hit on and b. I never get hit on. Basically I got really flustered and accidentally walked away from him mid converstion. doooo do dooooo......

on the plus side, we got a new bodem! bodem!

2 1/2 more years of this
then I will have a BA and can breathe.

The problem is I'm not willing to give up my work. But at the expense of taking longer to complete my degree, immense amounts of stress and meltdowns (fun for the roomies to deal with, thanks guys) and lowering my GPA. Honours degree? Would be cool. Grad school New York? Heck yes.

I dont know with my relationship with dance is anymore. My school life has turned entirely academic, which I enjoy. I'm maintaining my physicality through swimming, yoga and capoeira. My work life has become dedicated to the four children I work with, which makes it incredibly difficult to cut back on work hours (working 40 hour a week plus full time school equals no life). But what am I? A dancer? An autism support worker? A Biological Psych student? A hermit? A social flake? A workoholic? 

Last night I went to my first dance show in roughly a year. Made me cry to see the way those women move.

Anyways, Nat and I are working on a costume-specific/site specific piece. We had one rehearsal where I was in heels on the SFU roof, but we eventually got kicked off by security due to my yelling too loudly. Does this allow for my integrity as a dancer to remain?

I don't know if I'm even "Maria" anymore, whatever that means.

Maybe if I just focus on the intercellular spaces in my body, think about how the world actually moves through me, I can forget about this idea of "who". Dance will find me if its meant to be.

I watched a lot of so you think you can dance: canada and some show about fat chicks trying to find love today. 
No wonder we unplugged the cable.
I feel like the scum of the earth.

I got a journal again, so maybe I'll start writing in it. 
That and my computer broke, so it is very difficult to open and close which is a huge pissoff. What is the point of a laptop that isn't very portable? I mean, really.

So that, and I've been in an awful mood for the past while because my roommates (excl. Emilio) are hella messy. bleck.

And I got my textbooks fucking $420 later. Fuck school! And what is with me shopping for my texbooks directly across from Emilio's textbooks? Usually I'm in the Fine and Performing Arts section at the other side of the store but not this time!! MATH!? CHEM!???!!! I'm bracing myself......

well im finally on the raconteurs bandwagon. And the handsome furs. And its summer, which means I'm drunk way more than usual and skateboarding way more than usual. Which I guess is good. It also means I have bankles though (read: bruised ankles).

We went to the point tonight and I saw 10 separate people that I knew from High school. Fucking weird. You do all this random partying with people you actually talk to and then running into people is the weirdest thing. Especially when you remember who you were when you knew them but how different you are now from who you were then. 

I got a promotion at my one job so theres no turning back now.

We're back from sasquatch, it was a very fun fiasco. 

Now I have an exam on Thursday which I haven't studied for. And I missed a lecture because I had to work with the self injurious autistic kids. 

I've decided I'm not going back to dance. I'm going to take science courses instead and work in ABA. Maybe get my own classes running if I want, but really I'm not totally down for the effort. We'll see what happens.

like sunbeams and you will always look lovely."

is due tuesday and worth 25% of my grade, but I have not touched it in three days!

"Even your greatest enemy has more points of harmony than of disharmony. And so, as you are wanting to interact with a being that you are not getting along with, with a being that rings your warning bells continually, if you will intend to see that which you approve of, if you intend to see that which you like, then you will literally begin to solicit from that being, those things.

Are you understanding that in every relationship you have -- whenever you are having unpleasant experiences, you are attracting the unpleasant experience because that is where you are giving your attention?"

Abraham Hicks

It's been apparent for me in the past few days. I don't know why "8" is all of a sudden a magic number, but now that it's been 8 months I feel my attitude has changed. I woke up annoyed. I've been putting my thoughts on the things that annoy me, when in fact nothing has actually changed about the nature of our relationship--it's just as innocent, loving, and beautiful as it always was. But putting all of this emphasis in my own mind about 8 months, all the expectations that I had kept at bay about "THE FUTURE" now seem ...appropriate. How absurd! Why can't I just see a beautiful, sleeping creature? Why do I see my own laziness and faults?

In a sense, I've always combatted my own fear of failure with a strategy to prove how untrue it is, instead of just disregarding the absurdity of it completely. I used to be gung-ho about dancing, now I'm gung-ho about waking up at the same time every day and getting good grades. Maybe its like how we shield our eyes when someone is embarrassed and utterly humiliated, or somehow deeply injured. We know the pain on some level, and the threat to who we think we are is so great that we would rather not have to think about it. Is it guilt? Maybe it's guilt about your own "sins," needlessly trying to protect someone else, because you wern't able to avoid those same "mistakes". Trying to save the world from pain and suffering.

What a typical Maria story. Thats not love, thats what the ego tries to say is love, so that we can hold on to the misperceptions that led us to believe in failure in the first place. It's comfortable because it's what you know, but its really not what I want.

What is that quote? "Change your mind and the world will follow?" something along those lines..

I always find useless junk to fill my head with and right now its about work! and making schedules! Because I have 4 jobs!! haaah! Its like a puzzle and its kind of fun to think of all the different ways they can fit together, and you can make up lots of different ways but when it comes down to it there's really only one way, and thats the way it is right now. 

And besides, i should really be analyzing a research paper about the effects of summer reading intervention on children in grades 1 through 5. Fudging educational psych.

I'm tired. But at the same time I have breaks in my day and I get bored because I don't remember what it's like to have free time. What do you do with your free time?

I had a dream last night that I was having a baby, so I went to the hospital. The nurse told me I'd be in labour for 4 hours so I went to the waiting room to see what family was there and see them. Then we were cheering because it was a boy (or maybe it was a girl?) so the nurse came out and brought me my baby, which was awfully big and kicking around. Then we went home and the baby wouldn't do what I wanted it to, and then it turned into a fly and it was so small I couldn't even see it any more. And it was talking back.

Then I was at a rock concert with emilio, and we decided to get married. So I went in my closet and looked for a nice enough dress, and we decided to get married by the rocking horse swing in the back yard of the house I grew up in. My dad and my mom were there, and we were going to make up our vows on the spot. It was all very rushed and improvised.

first pattern I made up myself! (well, largely modified anyways..)

CO 8 stitches. 
Knit in stockinette stitch
Row 1: knit
Row 2: purl
Row 3: knit 1, kfb, knit remaining until 2nd last, kfb, knit last
Row 4: as row 3 but purling sts
Row 5: Knit 6, yo, knit remaining [yo created opening for button]
Row 6: as row 4
Row 7: as row 3
Continue for 4 rows, or until flap is long enough and work is wide enough to cover front 1/2 of camera
Knit in stockinette stitch until work is long enough to fold over and cover whole camera (minus flap)
I think my purpose here is just to question.
